Here's an example of improper use of the `java.util.ResourceBundle` class that could lead to a vulnerability:

```java
import java.util.ResourceBundle;

public class VulnerableClass {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        //Load the properties file using the class name
        ResourceBundle rb = ResourceBundle.getBundle("com.example.MyClass");
        String propValue = rb.getString("myProp");
        System.out.println(propValue);
    }
}
```
In this example, the `ResourceBundle.getBundle()` method is used to load a property file using the class name instead of the more secure `classloader.getResourceAsStream()`. This makes it easy for attackers to replace the property file with their own malicious version, which could contain sensitive information or allow them to execute arbitrary code.

To mitigate this vulnerability, you can load the property file using the classloader like this:

```java
import java.util.PropertyResourceBundle;
import java.lang.ClassLoader;

public class SaferClass {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        ClassLoader cl = VulnerableClass.class.ClassLoader();
        PropertyResourceBundle rb = new PropertyResourceBundle(cl.getResourceAsStream("com/example/MyClass.properties"));
        String propValue = rb.getString("myProp");
        System.out.println(propValue);
    }
}
```

